TITLE: Demonstrating UTF-8 Buffer Encoding Changes in Node.js
DESCRIPTION: Shows the difference in Buffer encoding behavior before and after the security update. The new behavior replaces unmatched surrogate pairs with the Unicode replacement character (U+FFFD) instead of allowing invalid UTF-8 sequences.
SOURCE: https://github.com/nodejs/nodejs.org/blob/main/apps/site/pages/en/blog/vulnerability/openssl-and-utf8.md#2025-04-21_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
// Prior to these releases:
new Buffer('ab\ud800cd', 'utf8');
// <Buffer 61 62 ed a0 80 63 64>

// After this release:
new Buffer('ab\ud800cd', 'utf8');
// <Buffer 61 62 ef bf bd 63 64>

// This is an explicit conversion to a Buffer, but the implicit
// .write('ab\ud800cd') also results in the same pattern
websocket.write(new Buffer('ab\ud800cd', 'utf8'));
// This would result in the client disconnecting.
```

